          "title": "The call to the bride — forget, bow, receive (45:10-12)",
          "body": "The psalm's pivot at verse 10 is one of the most demanding passages in the entire Psalter. 'Listen, O daughter, give attention and incline your ear: forget your people and your father's house' (45:10). The triple call to attention — listen, give attention, incline your ear — signals the weight of what follows. What follows is a command to rupture identity: forget your people. In Old Testament covenant theology, 'your people and your father's house' is not merely family — it is ethnic identity, religious tradition, and the whole social structure that formed you. Ruth's famous declaration to Naomi (Ruth 1:16-17) uses the same vocabulary of people-transfer: 'your people shall be my people, and your God my God.' The call to the bride is the call of covenant: total reorientation of identity and loyalty toward a new Lord. Then the consequence: 'the King will desire your beauty' (45:11). The desire (*avah*) is the King's active, personal longing — not passive approval but seeking out. And the ground for submission is stated plainly: 'because He is your Lord, bow down to Him' (45:11). Allegiance is grounded in identity, not in personal feeling. The daughter of Tyre, the wealthiest outsider, will then seek her favor (45:12) — the one who submitted to the King receives international standing she could never have achieved in her father's house."
