          "body": "The psalm closes with two final promises and one personal vow. The promise to the King: 'In place of your fathers will be your sons; you shall make them princes in all the earth' (45:16). The dynastic succession is simultaneously historical and eschatological — no single Israelite king's sons became princes 'in all the earth,' but the Son of David whose throne endures 'forever and ever' (45:6) will do precisely this (Revelation 5:10: 'You have made them to be a kingdom and priests to our God; and they will reign upon the earth'). Then the psalmist steps into the poem's final moment as its agent of transmission: 'I will cause Your name to be remembered in all generations' (45:17). The psalmist has shifted from describing a wedding to making a vow of proclamation. He will be the instrument through which this King's name outlasts every dynasty. The final line confirms it: 'therefore the peoples will give You thanks forever and ever' (45:17). The poem that began with one poet's overflowing heart ends with all peoples' unending thanksgiving. The movement is not incidental — it traces the logic of proclamation: one heart overflows, the tongue becomes a pen, the pen becomes permanent Scripture, Scripture is proclaimed across generations, and the nations praise. Psalm 45 is its own best argument for why it was written."
